---
import BaseLayout from '../../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<BaseLayout title="Acute Myocardial Infarction" description="Simulation case for acute myocardial infarction management.">
  <div class="breadcrumb">
    <a href={base}>Home</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <a href={`${base}cases/`}>Cases</a>
    <span>›</span>
    <span>Acute Myocardial Infarction</span>
  </div>

  <div class="case-header">
    <span class="card-tag">Cardiac</span>
    <h1>Acute Myocardial Infarction</h1>
    <div class="case-meta">
      <span>⏱ Duration: 45 minutes</span>
      <span>📊 Difficulty: Intermediate</span>
      <span>👥 Team Size: 3–5</span>
      <span>🏥 Setting: Emergency Department</span>
    </div>
    <div class="tags" style="margin-top:1rem;">
      <span class="tag">Emergency</span>
      <span class="tag">ACLS</span>
      <span class="tag">ECG</span>
      <span class="tag">Cardiac</span>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Case Overview</h2>
    <p>
      A 58-year-old male, Mr. James Carter, presents to the Emergency Department via EMS with a
      chief complaint of crushing, substernal chest pain (8/10) that began 90 minutes ago at rest.
      The pain radiates to his left arm and jaw. He is diaphoretic, anxious, and reports nausea.
    </p>
    <p>
      Learners must rapidly assess the patient, obtain and interpret a 12-lead ECG, activate the
      cardiac catheterization lab, and manage the patient according to current STEMI guidelines
      while maintaining clear team communication and a focus on door-to-balloon time.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Patient Information</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Name:</strong> James Carter</li>
      <li><strong>Age:</strong> 58 years</li>
      <li><strong>Gender:</strong> Male</li>
      <li><strong>Weight:</strong> 88 kg</li>
      <li><strong>PMH:</strong> Hypertension, Hyperlipidemia, Type 2 Diabetes</li>
      <li><strong>Medications:</strong> Metformin 1000 mg BID, Lisinopril 10 mg daily, Atorvastatin 40 mg nightly</li>
      <li><strong>Allergies:</strong> Penicillin (rash)</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Initial Vital Signs</h2>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>BP:</strong> 152/94 mmHg</li>
      <li><strong>HR:</strong> 98 bpm (regular)</li>
      <li><strong>RR:</strong> 20 breaths/min</li>
      <li><strong>SpO₂:</strong> 94% on room air</li>
      <li><strong>Temp:</strong> 37.1°C</li>
      <li><strong>GCS:</strong> 15</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Learning Objectives</h2>
    <ul class="objective-list">
      <li>Perform a rapid, systematic assessment of a patient with acute chest pain</li>
      <li>Acquire and correctly interpret a 12-lead ECG for STEMI changes</li>
      <li>Initiate appropriate pharmacological interventions (aspirin, nitroglycerin, heparin, P2Y12 inhibitor)</li>
      <li>Activate the cardiac catheterization lab within door-to-balloon time guidelines (&lt;90 minutes)</li>
      <li>Demonstrate effective closed-loop communication and team leadership</li>
      <li>Communicate clearly with the patient and family regarding diagnosis and plan</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Scenario Progression</h2>
    <h4>Phase 1 – Initial Assessment (0–10 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Patient arrives with EMS report. Learners perform primary survey, obtain 12-lead ECG
      (shows ST elevations in leads II, III, aVF — inferior STEMI), initiate oxygen, and
      establish IV access.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 2 – Intervention (10–30 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Cardiology activation, antiplatelet and anticoagulation therapy, patient develops
      ventricular tachycardia requiring cardioversion.
    </p>
    <h4>Phase 3 – Stabilization &amp; Transfer (30–45 min)</h4>
    <p>
      Post-cardioversion stabilization, cath lab transport preparation, and family communication.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="content-section">
    <h2>Debriefing Guide</h2>
    <ul>
      <li>Was the ECG obtained and interpreted within the first 10 minutes?</li>
      <li>Were all required medications given in the correct doses and order?</li>
      <li>How was team communication managed during the arrhythmia?</li>
      <li>Was the door-to-balloon goal achieved? What could improve the timeline?</li>
      <li>How was the patient and family kept informed throughout the scenario?</li>
    </ul>
  </div>

  <div style="margin-top: 2rem;">
    <a href={`${base}cases/`} class="btn btn-primary" style="background: var(--color-primary); color: #fff;">← Back to Cases</a>
  </div>
</BaseLayout>
